comments.comment:
See AbstractClaimCaseDTOMapperTest.map(). This has calls a number of sub methods, each of which has differnt branches. Testing these in the top level method would be very unclear, hence the following is way easier to understand:

@Test
	public void map() {
		new Expectations(mapper) {
			{
				// Include expectations block as we dont want to execute the real methods
				mapper.populateCaseAttributes(claimCaseDTO, ocCaseForAbsence);
				mapper.populateLeaveRequestAttributes(claimCaseDTO, leaveRequest);
				mapper.populateOccupation(claimCaseDTO, leaveRequest);
				mapper.populateOtherAttributes(claimCaseDTO, leaveRequest);
			}
		};

		final ClaimCaseDTO mappedBO = mapper.map(sourceBo);

		// Step 1 creates the BO via subclass
		assertThat(mappedBO, is(claimCaseDTO));

		// Step 2 populates common data
		assertThat(mappedBO, is(claimCaseDTO));

		// Step 3 completes the BO via subclass
		assertThat(completeObjectCalledWithExpectedValues, is(true));

		new VerificationsInOrder(1) {
			{
				mapper.populateCaseAttributes(claimCaseDTO, ocCaseForAbsence);
				mapper.populateLeaveRequestAttributes(claimCaseDTO, leaveRequest);
				mapper.populateOccupation(claimCaseDTO, leaveRequest);
				mapper.populateOtherAttributes(claimCaseDTO, leaveRequest);
			}
		};
	}
}

Then there are unit tests for each of populateCaseAttributes, populateLeaveRequestAttributes, populateOccupation and populateOtherAttributes, which are also really simple.

IMO this is much better than one public method with 100 tests for different branches.

Its left it there as an indication of the type of value to put in, otherwise the person could put &lt;Integer&gt; &lt;Boolean&gt; etc incorrectly. It just a guide for customisation. I can remove if you think its confusing, but then it would just become an empty property, as follows:

